    <div class="prose">
      <p class="lead">Parts 1 and 2 covered the evolution and the critical analysis. This piece is for people who've absorbed both and are now asking: if I accept that the pattern is real but limited — what would I actually do about it?</p>

      <p>Instead of abstract frameworks, I'm going to walk through what FreshRoute — the produce distributor from Parts 1 and 2 — would do if they decided to implement this. The phases, the guardrails, the failures they'd encounter, and the honest cost considerations.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="section-rule"><hr></div>

    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Step Zero: Are the Foundations Ready?</h2>

      <p>Before anything else, an honest assessment. Building continuous decision systems on top of unreliable data amplifies problems. It doesn't solve them.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="readiness">
      <div class="readiness-col green">
        <h4>Ready to Build</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Inventory data is accurate and updated in real time</li>
          <li>Core systems have accessible APIs</li>
          <li>Team already uses AI tools informally</li>
          <li>Someone bridges operations and data on the team</li>
          <li>You can define what "good" looks like for key decisions</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="readiness-col amber">
        <h4>Ready for Workflows First</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Data exists but lives across spreadsheets and silos</li>
          <li>Some systems have APIs, others don't</li>
          <li>Team uses AI ad hoc but hasn't structured it</li>
          <li>Verification criteria would need to be designed from scratch</li>
          <li>No one formally bridges operations and data</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="readiness-col red">
        <h4>Fix Foundations First</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Inventory accuracy below 90%</li>
          <li>Core systems lack integration capabilities</li>
          <li>No team member has used AI tools at work</li>
          <li>Processes are undocumented or inconsistent</li>
          <li>Daily firefighting still dominates the schedule</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <span class="callout-label">If you're in the amber or red columns</span>
      <p>That's not a failure — it's clarity about where to invest next. Data quality, system integration, and AI literacy come first. The continuous decision systems will still be there when the foundations are ready.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="section-rule"><hr></div>

    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Which Processes Go First?</h2>

      <p>Not every process benefits from continuous decision-making. FreshRoute would evaluate candidates against four questions:</p>

      <p><strong>Frequency.</strong> How often does this decision happen? Daily or more justifies the investment. Monthly probably doesn't.</p>

      <p><strong>Verification clarity.</strong> Can you objectively measure whether the decision was good? Stockout rates and delivery timeliness are measurable. "Was this the right strategic call?" isn't.</p>

      <p><strong>Cost of being wrong.</strong> Overpaying by a small margin on one order is acceptable risk. Losing a key supplier relationship isn't.</p>

      <p><strong>Data accessibility.</strong> Does the system have access to the information it needs? If the critical data lives in someone's memory or in an email attachment, the system can't use it.</p>
    </div>

